Landed briefly in the  field about 15ft. From 23rd st and 80 ft south of me until it was spooked by an oncoming truck. I watched it for nearly 40 minutes after that as it repeatedly swooped the woods in effort to pick off a crow from the large roost (4 Rock doves also flushed), aggressively reacted to a Red tailed Hawk, repeatedly showed aggression to a female Harrier -  even facing talons at one point.  those interactions gave great comparative opportunities as they were virtually equal in size - though there was no ID question regarding the Per. From first sight). Peregrine hunted the eastern field and woods significantly before departing North East - a nice treat after having a couple of somewhat elusive views in Otsego last week that I wanted to ID as peregrine but didn't quite have enough good looks. County bird for me.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS421972102	2018-02-16 15:54:18	11575	species	Peregrine Falcon	Falco peregrinus			1					United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Baraga	US-MI-013					Ojibwa Beach and Sand Point	L888864	H	46.7808284	-88.4702289	2016-08-05	18:20:00	obsr713660	S30991606	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	80	4.023		2	1	G1873713	0	1	0		By foot	Juvenile hunting on beach	
URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS249364103	2018-08-05 13:45:44	11575	species	Peregrine Falcon	Falco peregrinus			1					United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Barry	US-MI-015	US-MI_1655	23			Barry SGA--Otis Lake	L782383	H	42.6075632	-85.4113581	2014-04-30	07:30:00	obsr451079	S18148992	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	205	1.127		2	1		0	1	1			As Jack Wykoff and I were standing in a clearing I noticed a bird high over Otis Lake but headed my way.  The wings were long and more narrow than the wings of Accipiters like Cooper's Hawk and Buteos like Red-tailed Hawk.  The primaries on the pointed wings did not have a fingered appearance.  The tail was long and narrow, the wing beats were shallow but powerful, the flight direct.  I recognized it as a large falcon, larger than Kestrel, Merlin, or Sharp-shinned Hawk but smaller than Gyrfalcon.  Jack spotted it as it drew in its wings and lost altitude, going from "way up there" to tree top height in an incredibly short time at an angle of about 45 degrees or maybe steeper.  It passed over our heads at 30-40 yards, momentarily stopping in a tree behind us.  When above, the bird appeared dark but as it flew from the tree it appeared grayish.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS291470249	2021-04-01 08:09:46.706605	11575	species	Peregrine Falcon	Falco peregrinus			2				Male, Adult (1); Female, Adult (1)	United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Bay	US-MI-017		12			Karn Plant (restricted access)	L492403	H	43.6460134	-83.8363266	2015-01-17	11:00:00	obsr350280	S21383042	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	105	8.047		1	1		0	1	0			A pair of PEFA were hunting Rock Pigeons in tandem around the tall smoke stack of the Karn Plant.  They would lift then swoop down in rapid descent after their prey.  All of the ROPI scattered, leaving just the PEFA pair to swoop around the stack with great ease in the strong southerly breeze.  An hour and a half later, I noted them flying above the Weadock building and one of them had a ROPI in tow.  The ROPI was still struggling and the PEFA was pecking at it while flying with ROPI feathers flying in the wind.  Both PEFA then disappeared on top of the Weadock building to consume their prey.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS436892766	2020-05-06 19:08:04	11575	species	Peregrine Falcon	Falco peregrinus			2					United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Bay	US-MI-017		12			Bay Co. to Saginaw Co. River Rail Trail	L4996394	H	43.5628593	-83.9123145	2016-10-17	09:45:00	obsr350280	S32091106	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	135	9.656		1	1		0	1	0		This is a new, paved rail trail that begins at the east end of Hotchkiss Rd just east of South Euclid.  The roughly ten mile round trip trail winds south along the west side of the Saginaw River and passes through wooded areas, farm fields, mudflats, and Crow Island State Game Area.  This will be a very good birding location for waterbirds, raptors, and passerines. The distance may deter birders but is easily do-able on a bicycle.  I birded casually as my brother and I biked the trail.	We were royally treated by a pair of Peregrine Falcons that were hunting over a large, freshly harvested corn field.  One of them landed on something and the other one flew up relatively high then swooped down on the unsuspecting Peregrine and nabbed its prey.  The 'robbed' Peregrine spent at least five minutes giving chase to the cargo carrying 'robber' that included a couple of passes right over our heads.  I could tell the prey was some type of bird as it dangled from it's talons.  The chase continued to the south of us and out of sight.  Another one of those "being in the right place at the right time" moments!

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS375655517	2020-04-26 14:04:25	11575	species	Peregrine Falcon	Falco peregrinus			2					United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Calhoun	US-MI-025		23			Battle Creek	L4292862	P	42.3202141	-85.1822698	2016-02-20	08:30:00	obsr516878	S27708559	Stationary	P21	EBIRD	25			2	0		0	1	1		Seeking Peregrines with Pat Deventer.	Downtown Battle Creek. Viewed from the parking lot off State Street west. Resident pair on the ledges of the  tall building (Heritage Tower) directly across the way on Michigan Ave. ----Large, stocky falcons with relatively short tails, and neat moustaches. Wind was such that they could do quite a bit of planing flight without wing beats. When they did have to flap they looked very "bat-like". Excellent light, some amazingly swift passes right in front of us, lots of "playing" in the wind pressure gradients around the tall building.----Delightful !

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS310423208	2016-09-29 22:31:34	11575	species	Peregrine Falcon	Falco peregrinus			1					United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Chippewa	US-MI-033	US-MI_1653		USFWS_225		Whitefish Point	L140452	H	46.7690010	-84.9530029	2015-04-15	10:45:00	obsr341304	S22891147	Stationary	P21	EBIRD	315			2	1	G1223049	0	1	0		EDITED and FINIALIZED  REPORT (April 23, 2105 11:25am)  - amazing raptor watch day - Bret Davis: the official counter was very informative and helpful - our focus was on enjoying the movement of raptors on their spring migration - counts of raptors reported here are accurate for the author, all of which either match or fall short of the numbers reported by the official counter - I and Dave enjoyed the viewing (I attempted to get some usable phototgraphs) - numbers reported here are reflective of the details extracted from photographs taken on the day, numerous species over a number of hours with birds coming northeast towards the viewing platform and then some of them returning to the southwest rather than crossing Lake Superior - full sunshine with a light wind which changed directions a number of times during our visit but remain favourable to the hawk movement - highlight was a Peregrine which moved across the dunes in front of our viewing position almost at eye level and not far out - my attempts to get to my camera failed but all had a good look - temperature climbed steady in the bright sunshine and more than 20 non-raptor species were seen and/or heard - strong movement of Sandhill Cranes - two small and fast moving birds came through which were initial thought to be Chimney Swifts, my attempts at a photo were not successful and my attention was not fully on the birds (which came separately) and my experience with Swifts is very limited - the conversation at the time was that they were Swifts but no evidence was attained so it has been removed from this report -  1600+ photos  of raptors and some of non-raptors to review - at the time of this report being finalized a number of sub-species of raptors were deemed "rare" for this location and time of year along with some numbers deemed "high" for the timing, this report takes all of that into consideration and has provided photographic evidence when available - numbers are accurate or deliberately understated and noted as conservative estimates rather than using 'X' - I have begun to prepare a photo essay on my flickr account  https://www.flickr.com/photos/agawa2yukon/--Under the title "PHOTO ESSAY WPBO ..." which has more than 260 edited frames from the day - additional photographic evidence for the accuracy of this report can be viewed in that essay--http://ebird.org/content/canada/news/identifying-northern-red-tailed-hawks/

Marina	L3013519	P	47.1252681	-88.5717505	2014-07-19	09:45:00	obsr48314	S19301926	Stationary	P21	EBIRD	5			1	1		0	1	1			Using binoculars only (no scope available) there were three individuals in the nest box attached near top of southern structure of lift bridge. (Not able to accurately discern whether any were adults.) A few minutes later, I saw a falcon (while driving a car on the Houghton side of the end of the bridge), with a pigeon (?) in its beak flying just above the cars. I read about this nesting location in the local newspaper; a local birder spoke about them previous night at a library (unfortunately, I read the article 3 hours too late). There is information about the nest site currently (8/1/2014) on the MDOT website (posted 7/28/2014) here: http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0,4616,7-151--334009--,00.html, which indicates 3 chicks fledged here this year. I did not take any photos.

Short period of rain in P.M.  Warm front approached and passed from the SW, Then cold front was approaching from the WNW toward end of count.--Massive movement first noted earlier at Minden/M25 and all along the route proceeding to Kinch Rd.  Incredible numbers of blackbirds ( mainly grackles and red-wings) and robins continued steadily for two hours with scattered flocks continuing until the rain started. Periodic counts revealed blackbirds averaging at 200 birds per minute!!  Robins clocking in at 20 per minute.  All birds were headed in an easterly direction following the shoreline to .2 miles inland.

PORT CRESCENT STATE PARK SITE--Observations A RECORD-BREAKER!! Ended the day with our second MIKI of the count season :) And, oy, the broadwings!----Flight notes: Heading back home to Midland an hour after close of count, there was a huge storm system coming in from the west over Saginaw Bay. Hundreds of hawks were milling around Sand Point (their jumping-off point across the Saginaw Bay) having no chance of going around the storm, thus likely descended for the day. No raptors were seen more than 1 mile past Sand Point, supporting the theory that they island hop across Saginaw Bay to get to the Arenac and Iosco County shores to the west. --Non-raptor Notes Common Nighthawks descending at the end of count:12--SACR:10----Visitors: Danny Akers joined me for the final 90 minutes of the count. As he was departing, he stated I would have something rare flying through now that he was exiting. He hadn't even made it out of the park before a MIKI flew right overhead. I messaged him and he was able to spot the bird cruising along the beach a short distance from the park!! His final Michigan bird as he departed for IOWA :)

Nested at Michigan State Office Building. John Will confirmed nesting by finding one fledged juvenile on 8/20/2004. Female was unbanded, but male was banded, known as Jake, fledged in wild in 2002,  Mississauga, Ont. Listed in Midwest Peregrine Falcon Restoration 2004 Annual Report as nest #67.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS251777128	2014-05-08 17:26:08	11575	species	Peregrine Falcon	Falco peregrinus			1					United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Kent	US-MI-081		23			DeBruine Home	L983294	P	43.1232030	-85.3578646	2011-03-14	14:45:00	obsr413935	S18289071	Incidental	P20	EBIRD				6	0	G891910	0	1	1		From Birdventure:----March 24, 2011:--Barrow's Goldeneye and Red-necked Grebe on March 11:  almost unbeatable!!!  Snow Bunting, Hooded Merganser, and Wilson's Snipe (Montcalm Co.) last Saturday:  great!!  Now it's Monday, and we're celebrating a mini Hawk Fest at our house!--      I used my short afternoon recess time today to take a jog in search of local Yellow-rumped Warblers.  I missed them, but ended up finding a Red-shouldered Hawk and several other buteos circling high above our house.  This was exciting!  I hollered at Nathan (who was birding the woods) to head out to the field and start counting raptors.  In no time at all he had picked up several raptor species.  After rigging up a talkie-walkie connection, I headed back to my bedroom where I resumed my AP test preparatory studies.----The talkie-walkie "hotline" stayed active from the beginning: --"Red-tailed Hawk--two of them flying along the orchard fencerow way back there"...--..."Kestrel flying over, do you need it?"...  --Two minutes later:  "Sharpie and Cooper's, both almost gone... and 7 Killdeer."--"Possible Harrier, gone now...  ...and Turkey Vulture, two, three, four of them..."--"Just tell me the real and big stuff, you know--I'm trying to do my Physics."--..."hey, juvie Eagle ... it's a Bald Eagle!"  A little later:  "Another Bald Eagle!"----Static buzz and wireless bird-alert broadcasting went on like this for several minutes.  Finally I got a blurb:  "I've got a large falcon species!"...  A little background buzz...  "It's a PEREGRINE FALCON!!!".  I dashed out of my room, pulled my shoes on in record time and got out in the field.  That was a new yard bird for me!  Nathan was out there snapping pictures with my camera.  Every one of my little siblings had also heard the news.  They were stumbling over snow and muddy field grass on their dash to the crest of the hawk-watching knoll.  Amid lots of oohs and aahs from my siblings, all demanding scope views for their lifer, I managed just two brief glimpses.  But It was 100% Peregrine Falcon!  Year bird!!  Yard bird!!!----[image]--Peregrine Falcon (yes, very meager evidence)--After plummeting back into my bedroom chair to study AP Physics, the buzz kept on going, but things began settling down.  The Peregrine Falcon was diving and returning to his perch several times, and every little movement was enthusiastically broadcasted by the more juvenile observers.  But after the Peregrine's departure, and one possible Merlin fly-by a few minutes later, everything sunk back into the normal "boring" succession of Nathan announcing Red-tailed Hawks, Great Blue Herons, Killdeer, and Goldfinches.--     But it was great, really great.  If I can continue to manage an average of one new species every day (until summer), I'm happy!  Hawk Fest at my house is on the go, and tomorrow's birds are yet to be seen...

Now it's Monday, and we're celebrating a mini Hawk Fest at our house!--      I used my short afternoon recess time today to take a jog in search of local Yellow-rumped Warblers.  I missed them, but ended up finding a Red-shouldered Hawk and several other buteos circling high above our house.  This was exciting!  I hollered at Nathan (who was birding the woods) to head out to the field and start counting raptors.  In no time at all he had picked up several raptor species. They were stumbling over snow and muddy field grass on their dash to the crest of the hawk-watching knoll. Yard bird!!!----[image]--Peregrine Falcon (yes, very meager evidence)--After plummeting back into my bedroom chair to study AP Physics, the buzz kept on going, but things began settling down.  The Peregrine Falcon was diving and returning to his perch several times, and every little movement was enthusiastically broadcasted by the more juvenile observers.  But after the Peregrine's departure, and one possible Merlin fly-by a few minutes later, everything sunk back into the normal "boring" succession of Nathan announcing Red-tailed Hawks, Great Blue Herons, Killdeer, and Goldfinches.--     But it was great, really great.  If I can continue to manage an average of one new species every day (until summer), I'm happy!  Hawk Fest at my house is on the go, and tomorrow's birds are yet to be seen...

Birds were sheltering from a strong E/NE wind and three days of heavy rain during whch 2-3 inches of rain fell. Due to the late leafout this year, warblers were foraging near or along sand beaches, whcih seemed to offer the most food in the form of midge hatches.----Temp. around 43 F, and constant heavy drizzle

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS443293530	2016-11-15 21:56:00	11575	species	Peregrine Falcon	Falco peregrinus			1				Unknown Sex, Adult (1)	United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Lenawee	US-MI-091		22			417 State St	L5083991	P	41.8954253	-84.0353894	2016-11-15	12:10:00	obsr771929	S32566093	Incidental	P20	EBIRD				1	0		0	1	1			I had just stepped outside my back door and was smelling a rose in my garden when I became aware of the falcon's presence, taking off just above my head and flying behind a neighbors home.  It must have been perching on my locust tree or the corner of my tall Victorian house.  ----It was a large falcon with broad, long and very pointed wings.  The shape of the wings was quite distinctive and made a strong impression on me.  I observed that its wingbeats were slow and very powerful.  It was quite large, about 80% the size and weight of a red-tailed hawk.  The wings looked a rather uniform light bluish gray from below, and the body and tail were similar without stripes.  It had the standard underside coloration of an adult tundra Peregrine.   I did not see its head markings from my angle of view.  I only saw it for a couple seconds before it was gone, and it took my breath away.----About 20 minutes before I observed the bird, my girlfriend heard it vocalizing as she got out of her car and entered the house.  It was making the characteristic and strange "kak kak kak" call.----This is the 5th time this year that she or I have seen this large falcon in my city.  We did not log the earlier sightings to eBird as they were frustratingly brief glimpses.  Today I feel more confidence in what I saw and believe it confirms the earlier sightings.----In August I saw a similar bird take off from my back yard and fly down my driveway.  As today, it was a sighting I was unprepared for, and the falcon was gone in an instant.   Twice since then it was seen roosting in a tall maple at the end of our street, but after stepping inside to get my binoculars it was gone before I could study it.  Once my girlfriend observed it while driving.----I should note also that I live just two blocks from downtown Adrian.  Many pigeons roost on the old firehouse tower at the end of my street.	
URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS448530858	2016-12-12 15:37:30	11575	species	Peregrine Falcon	Falco peregrinus			1				Male, Adult (1)	United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Lenawee	US-MI-091		22			417 State St	L5083991	P	41.8954253	-84.0353894	2016-12-11	16:40:00	obsr771929	S32971090	Incidental	P20	EBIRD				1	0		0	1	1			Continuing sighting for a local peregrine--the 6th time we have seen it in the last 4 months.  I was beginning to dig out my car in a snowstorm this afternoon when I noticed something large fly into the top of a tall spruce tree in my back yard.  When I looked up I saw it was the peregrine, a rather eerie sight in the quiet heavy snowfall.  I observed the bird for about a minute from a distance of 70'.  It had the coloration of a tundra adult--a bluish slate back, wings, and tail with a lighter breast.  I could resolve the dark sideburns on its side face with my naked eye.  The bird acted nervous and moved sideways from one spruce to the next, across a group of 5 trees.  I quietly went back into the house to get my binoculars, but as I came out again the bird flew away.  It disappeared very quickly with just a few beats of its wings.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS569740944	2018-01-21 10:03:11	11575	species	Peregrine Falcon	Falco peregrinus			1					United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Monroe	US-MI-115					Pte. Mouillee SGA	L248057	H	42.0146112	-83.2001495	2008-08-28	16:00:00	obsr218010	S42120829	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	120	8.047		1	0		1	1	0		I took a quick run down to Pt. Mouillee this afternoon (after work) despite the dark skies and threat of rain. I've always said that I wouldn't digiscope when skies are cloudy, and today I kept to that promise - of course it helps that I left the Coolpix P5000 in the car (grrr...). I missed the opportunity to digiscope several Bobolinks when I made the realization that I didn't have the camera in my vest. Oh, well! I decided then that I would not be distracted by photography and I would make an attempt at counting shorebirds in Cell 3.	parked the bike at the NW corner of Cell 3 and started to walk toward the hundreds of shorebirds scattered across the north end of the cell. No sooner did I raise my binoculars when I felt a sudden rush of wind and loud wingbeats in my right ear. A Peregrine Falcon shot past my head like a bullet and headed straight for the crowd of shorebirds in front of me. Quickly raising the D300 and Sigma 400mm I attempted to focus on the bird as it banked left and headed for the now-scattering flocks. Despite the somewhat low light I was able to follow the falcon as it made several swipes at passing Semipalmated Plovers and Sandpipers.

We were driving, when suddenly, something flew off and down from the pole. Wings were pointed, and the wings beats were strong and not spuratic. Shape was not hawklike. Falcon even tucked in its wings and dove down into the little water stream down there, to the right of us. Thought he was attacking some ducks down there, but he was just flying within inches of the water, before jetting back up, and perching yet again. Scared it about three times before it finally flew away. Peregrine was really booking it in the air! Might have been a female, since the overall colors were rather light.

Perched on top of a telephone pole. We were driving, when suddenly, something flew off and down from the pole. Wings were pointed, and the wings beats were strong and not spuratic. Shape was not hawklike. Falcon even tucked in its wings and dove down into the little water stream down there, to the right of us. Thought he was attacking some ducks down there, but he was just flying within inches of the water, before jetting back up, and perching yet again. Scared it about three times before it finally flew away. Peregrine was really booking it in the air! Might have been a female, since the overall colors were rather light. FOY #53

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS156804886	2021-04-01 07:57:44.81733	11575	species	Peregrine Falcon	Falco peregrinus			1					United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Oakland	US-MI-125		23			Mike's house (restricted access)	L628872	P	42.4837511	-83.3373493	2012-06-20		obsr168952	S11010755	Incidental	P20	EBIRD				1	1		0	1	1			A serendipitous moment. I looked through the trees at a half-dead shagbark hickory and saw blue Jays harassing a hawk. Then, I noticed a stunning teardrop (helmet). The bird was noticeably larger than the jays, and it had a brown back. Its neck was white. I could not see the breast. It had the feel of Copper's Hawk; Kestrels have the feel of a Mourning Dove. When it flew, I noticed pointy wings (it was a windless day, so point-winged accipitors was not an issue). It flew south, unfortunately under the tree line. Minutes later, I walked to a local school yard, thinking it might be perched there. Nothing. I eliminated accipitors by the helmet. I eliminated Kestrel by the size and lack of red on the back. The bird was basked in sunlight, not a shadow. Merlin lacks the stunning teardrop pattern. Prairie falcon is a non-issue. I have seen Peregrines within two miles of my house, but only in August. No reports or observations of nesting Kestrels this year, but they have nested within 2 miles in some years.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS590865992	2021-09-06 01:07:27.020192	11575	species	Peregrine Falcon	Falco peregrinus			1					United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Oakland	US-MI-125		23			Kensington Metropark--general	L389645	H	42.5284410	-83.6706485	2018-03-23	10:44:00	obsr185697	S43886154	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	135	3.219		1	1		0	1	1			I ran into David Amamoto (from WAS) at the Heron rookery and we chatted about the area birds.  Out of corner of my eye a medium sized raptor appeared (about crow size).  Considering the area and habitat I didn't initially think PEFA but noticed it didn't fit the description of a COHA as it had proportionally long pointed wings.  The bird flew away from us in a glide pattern with a flat-winged profile consistent with a Peregrine.  Upon closer inspection viewing through my binos I noticed that the bird had heavy streaking on its underparts as well.   I could not see the facial pattern as it flew away from us.  The overall description of it was a crow-sized bird with a slight build compared to a COHA or small male RTHA.------Comparing notes about the bird with David we both agreed it was a PEFA.  Unfortunately no pictures were obtained.----Jim

This sighting is via the falcon-cam (viewed from a remote computer) located on the falcon platform on the large chimney at the Grand Haven Light and Power Plant on Harbor Island in Grand Haven (Ottawa County). The site to view this platform is http://199.116.53.3/  Peregrine falcons unsuccessfully nested here in 2000. Falcons successfully nested here from 2001 through 2013. There was no attempted nesting in 2014, however, the birds were in the vicinity. The last time a pair was seen at the platform was 3/15/15. Since then, one adult has been periodically been seen at the platform. Today is the first reported from the Falcon-Cam on eBird.

I had yet another great IWMMP survey at Shiawassee NWR with eight new year birds that included Pectoral Sandpiper, Dunlin, and Caspian Tern.  The highlight, though, happened not fifty feet from me.  I was observing Greater Yellowlegs on the far edge of a moist soil unit channel when they started to fly from my right to left.  To my great surprise, a Peregrine Falcon slammed one of them into the water, flew behind me with its prey onto the dike I was on and then flew off with it.  Another Greater Yellowlegs flew in circles above it and was scolding the falcon.  Mate, perhaps?  It all happened in seconds but I've been rewinding that observation a number of times in my mind!  Beyond the 'ticks'...Reason 3,286 why I love birding...   :)

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS572818154	2018-02-10 13:32:17	11575	species	Peregrine Falcon	Falco peregrinus			1					United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Wayne	US-MI-163	US-MI_3847	22			Pte. Mouillee SGA--HQ	L492304	H	42.0403691	-83.1998062	2010-09-26	10:30:00	obsr218010	S42374196	Stationary	P21	EBIRD	120			6	1		0	1	0		I headed over to the boat launch, where Jeff Schultz was acting a head counter for the Detroit River Hawk Watch.  Things were a bit slow there until Jeff scoped several large kettles of Broad-winged Hawks (BWHA) south over Lake Erie.  David Boon and I offered to run down to Pt. Mouillee to get a more accurate count, so at 10:30 am we headed south.  Five minutes later we were standing on the observation deck at the headquarters. For the next hour things would be hopping, with a steady stream of Broad-wings flying east from Canada, and kettling in the clouds produced by the Fermi plant.  How Jeff could see these birds still boggles the mind. Circled together over toward GM buildings, then back, then over river, then back to SP where they were directly overhead for some time, then across river toward Canada. Noticeably larger than kestrel, similar in size to the ever-present ring-billed gulls at SP, but not as large as Cooper's hawk, for instance.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS302938493	2018-08-05 13:59:02	11575	species	Peregrine Falcon	Falco peregrinus			2				Male, Adult (1); Female, Adult (1)	United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Wayne	US-MI-163		23			Grace Lake (Visteon Pond)	L818015	H	42.2386218	-83.4312057	2015-03-13	12:20:00	obsr359041	S22335562	Stationary	P21	EBIRD	40			4	1	G1183963	0	1	0		Thin cloud cover, warm trend continues, very light winds, 50F	As we were observing and counting gulls in the small open patch of water, we noticed that gulls were lifting off and squawking. Then we saw the female PEFA flying in from the south side of the lake. The PEFA swooped and turned creating frenzy three times and on third turn into the middle of flock, it singled out one Ring-Billed Gull and took it down to the iced area. The gull was on its back and the PEFA was having difficulty getting to the back of the neck to finish the kill. Once the PEFA accomplished the kill, it flew with gull approximately 70 feet away to pull out gull's feathers. At this point a smaller PEFA, the male, attempted to share the meal but the female refused and caused male to fly back to its roost in large tree to the south side of lake. Almost immediately, a RLHA flew in and circled the PEFA and its kill three times and then flew away.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS640879764	2021-03-19 08:52:39.709488	11576	issf	Peregrine Falcon	Falco peregrinus	Peregrine Falcon (North American)	Falco peregrinus anatum	1				Unknown Sex and Age (1)	United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Clinton	US-MI-037		23			Looking Glass River	L1078560	P	42.8650816	-84.4614315	2018-07-18	05:45:00	obsr241827	S47278599	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	300	0.402		1	1		0	1	1		Drifted downriver to the south end of the big marsh before sunrise and sat for 1 hour by the mudflat and then returned to the landing. Temps- 54-71 degrees - no breeze, clear before sunrise and sunny afterwards. Mist coming off the water surface made focusing difficult.	Observed the bird 3 times. First time flying over the marsh edge on my left side as I headed downriver- noted the pointed wings and narrow tail - it landed in a dead tree behind me. I turned and glassed the bird - all I could see was a silhouette with the light behind rising in the east and  the air was misty.  I thought probably a Cooper's it appeared to be that overall size- so I drifted downriver and it appeared with in minutes overhead  and swirled once and dove at the ducks which were  about 20 or 30 yards off - once again still too misty. I could barely see the ducks and they had not flushed on my approach. About a hour later- the air was clearer- I had finished photographing the rail/sora, it came soaring up river about 15 feet over the surface- 25 yards off it appeared to dive slightly at the Sora I was watching which disappeared too quickly into the marsh grass. I viewed the bird without glasses- this time I was able to note a dark mustache mark on the face, ( it flew pass me left to right).  As it flew off it gained elevation and again the pointed wings and narrow tail was very evident. The length was similar to a Cooper's but the not the bulk of a one. Sorry no photo- it just caught me by surprise.

Perched along trail in snag. Too far from Grand Rapids to be one of the local birds and plumage seems to confirm it. Behavior was so out of whack for one of the local birds that i was shocked to see it here. Thin malar stripe, large white forehead and loral area, white chest and underparts, wingtips slightly beyond tail tip, corroborate the ID.
